Disabled GitLab Webhooks to the Older Jenkins Instance (jenkins-os-1):

The older Jenkins instance (jenkins-os-1) was not suitable for your project because it didn’t have all the required agents (nodes) with the necessary environment, such as Python 3.11.
The integration from GitLab to Jenkins was done via webhooks. Webhooks are a way for one application (GitLab) to send real-time data to another application (Jenkins) when specific events occur, such as a commit or a merge request.
Created a Multibranch Pipeline in the Newer Jenkins Instance:

Instead of relying on the old Jenkins instance, your manager created a new multibranch pipeline on a newer Jenkins instance that has all the necessary agents and configurations.
A multibranch pipeline in Jenkins automatically discovers branches and pull requests in a Git repository and creates corresponding Jenkins jobs for each branch. It is particularly useful for projects that have multiple branches under development.
Set Up Polling in the Multibranch Pipeline:

The multibranch pipeline is configured to poll GitLab for changes. This means Jenkins periodically checks the GitLab repository for any updates (e.g., new commits, new branches, or new merge requests) and triggers a build if changes are detected.
Why Your Manager Did This:
To Use the Correct Jenkins Instance with the Necessary Agents:

The older Jenkins instance (jenkins-os-1) did not have all the required agents, so jobs could fail or run into issues because of missing environments like Python 3.11.
To Simplify and Improve the Build Process:

A multibranch pipeline is more efficient for managing multiple branches. It eliminates the need to create separate jobs manually for each branch and can automatically handle new branches or pull requests.
It allows for better management of the CI/CD process for projects with multiple branches and is more integrated with GitLab's branching model.
To Reduce Configuration Overhead and Maintenance:

By using the multibranch pipeline, there is no need to configure and maintain separate webhooks for each branch. The pipeline automatically discovers branches and pull requests and creates corresponding Jenkins jobs.
It ensures that the CI/CD pipeline is up-to-date with the latest changes in the repository without manual intervention.
How It Works:
Multibranch Pipeline Setup:

In Jenkins, your manager created a new multibranch pipeline job.
This job is configured with the URL of the GitLab repository.
Jenkins automatically scans the repository for branches and pull requests.
Polling for Changes:

The multibranch pipeline is configured to poll the GitLab repository at a set interval (e.g., every minute, every 5 minutes).
Whenever Jenkins detects new commits, new branches, or updates to existing branches, it triggers a corresponding build.
Automatic Build for Each Branch:

Jenkins creates a separate pipeline for each branch detected in the GitLab repository.
For example, if you have branches main, develop, and feature/xyz, Jenkins will create separate pipelines for each of these.
Whenever there are changes in any of these branches, Jenkins triggers a build for that specific branch.
Benefits of Multibranch Pipeline:

Automatic Discovery: Jenkins automatically discovers new branches and pull requests.
Branch-Specific Configurations: Each branch can have its own Jenkinsfile, allowing for branch-specific build and test configurations.
Reduced Manual Work: No need to manually create or update Jenkins jobs for each branch.
Summary:
Why: The old Jenkins instance was lacking necessary agents, and the multibranch pipeline provides a more efficient way to manage and build multiple branches.
What: Your manager set up a multibranch pipeline on the newer Jenkins instance, configured it to poll GitLab for changes, and disabled the old webhook integration.
How: The multibranch pipeline scans the repository, automatically sets up jobs for each branch, and triggers builds based on the latest changes.
